ClassLass,<br><br>
As usual, you come up with tough, but good questions. What I had before my Vietnam War experience from a religoius sense was not much formally. I was more of a spiritual person and I felt inside that doing wrong things was wrong. My belief structure evolved from my Grandfather's teachings. He was a former Marine and NYPD officer.<br><br>
In Vietnam, by December, 1969, I ceased having any vestige of spirituality, and was very &quot;dead&quot; inside. It was a slow &quot;death&quot; caused by things piling up on each other, and was painless. I became numb. I have a photo of myself a buddy took of me on R&amp;R in Hong Kong, and I do not look &quot;alive&quot; in the least. I recently read it is called the 1000 yard stare. <br><br>
I remained in that state until two years ago when 'Nam stuff began really leaking out of the strong box in my mind, and I went over the edge. The stuff had been leaking out all along, and to compensate my behavior and dissociation took over. The only reason I lasted so long was that my job became the focus and outlet for this stuff, along with my family. <br><br>
Right now, I am rediscovering and redefining myself, and realizing that some of my lost spirituality was just put away for safe keeping! It is not yet sure it is safe enough to fully emerge, but it is peeking out.<br><br>
I find at this point in my life, that I must learn what it is to be and feel human, and therein lies my present connection with the works of Joseph Campbell, Native American Cultures, Eastern cultures, and the like. While I am not close to anything resembling an established religion, I feel the presence of a supreme being more strongly now than I have ever felt. <br><br>
I am now at a crossroads of sorts. I respect people who have strong sincere religous convictions, as well as those who do not. We must be decent to each other regardless of our personal directions. In that way, I feel I can learn again, and heal.<br><br>
Peace. 
